{"title_page": "Ave Maria School of Law", "text_new": "{{short description|Law School}}\n{{Infobox Law School\n | name           = Ave Maria School of Law\n | image          = AMSOL Logo.jpg\n | established    = 1999\n | type           = [[Private university|Private]]\n | head           = Kevin Cieply\n | city           = [[Naples, Florida|Naples]]\n | state          = [[Florida]]\n | country        = USA\n | coordinates    = {{coord|26.242147|-81.731321|type:edu|display=title,inline}}\n | [[US News and World Report|USNAWR]] Ranking = Tier Four\n | students       = 255\n | faculty        = 28\n | bar pass rate  = 52.6% (July 2019)<ref>https://www.floridabarexam.org/__85257bfe0055eb2c.nsf/52286ae9ad5d845185257c07005c3fe1/53ef72befcb1d3ec852584770066a147</ref>\n | annual tuition = $39,450\n | room and board = $13,131\n | homepage       = {{URL|http://www.avemarialaw.edu}}\n | aba profile    = [https://officialguide.lsac.org/Release/SchoolsABAData/SchoolPage/SchoolPage.aspx?sid=188]\n}}\n\n'''Ave Maria School of Law''', founded in 1999, is an [[American Bar Association|ABA]]-accredited [[Roman Catholic]] [[law school]] located in [[Naples, Florida]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanbar.org/groups/legal_education/resources/aba_approved_law_schools/in_alphabetical_order/|title=In Alphabetical Order|website=www.americanbar.org|language=en|access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref>\n\n== History and governance ==\n\n[[Tom Monaghan|Thomas S. Monaghan]], founder of [[Domino's Pizza]] and former owner of the [[Detroit Tigers]], supports the school through his Ave Maria Foundation and has served as the [[chairman of the board]] of governors of the school, which also includes [[Adam Maida|Adam Cardinal Maida]], and [[Frank Joseph Dewane]] and included, before their deaths, [[Edward Egan|Cardinal Edward Egan]], [[Bowie Kuhn]] and [[John Joseph O'Connor|John Cardinal O'Connor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://avemarialaw.edu/faculty/BoardOfGovernors|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121209070558/http://www.avemarialaw.edu/faculty/BoardOfGovernors|url-status=dead|title=Board of Governors List|archivedate=Dec 9, 2012|accessdate=Apr 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAve Maria School of Law was founded in 1999, and for the first nine years of its existence was located in [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]]. The law school's beginnings lie in discussions between future founding dean Bernard Dobranski and Monaghan. [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] Justice [[Antonin Scalia]] assisted in developing the school's curriculum, and in 1999 Supreme Court Justice [[Clarence Thomas]] delivered the school's first annual Ave Maria Lecture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=academics.Speakers|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612171923/http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=academics.Speakers|url-status=dead|title=Lectures|archivedate=Jun 12, 2010|accessdate=Apr 20, 2020}}</ref> Former professors include [[Robert Bork]].<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.avemarialaw.edu/page-section/history-timeline/|title = History Timeline\u2014Ave Maria School of Law|website = Ave Maria School of Law|language = en-US|access-date = 2016-03-11}}</ref>\n\nThe school moved from Ann Arbor, Michigan, to Naples, Florida, opening in the new location in August 2009.\n\nKevin Cieply became the third president and dean of the law school in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avemarialaw.edu/faculty/presidentanddean |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-07-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714161054/http://www.avemarialaw.edu/faculty/presidentanddean |archivedate=2014-07-14 }}</ref>\n\n== Academics and curriculum ==\n\nAve Maria School of Law offers a full-time three year [[Juris Doctor]] (J.D.) program that complements a traditional legal education based on the [[Socratic Method]] with an emphasis on how the law intersects with the Catholic intellectual tradition and [[natural law]] philosophy. The curriculum of Ave Maria School of Law includes a three-semester Legal Analysis, Writing, and Research Program as well as several required courses that focus on law and [[ethics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=academics.curriculum|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716130259/https://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=academics.curriculum|url-status=dead|title=Curriculum|archivedate=Jul 16, 2011|accessdate=Apr 20, 2020}}</ref> The school also offers various summer courses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://avemarialaw.edu/Content/academics/Schedule_Summer2014_Alpha.pdf|title=Archived copy|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414033902/http://avemarialaw.edu/Content/academics/Schedule_Summer2014_Alpha.pdf|archivedate=2015-04-14|accessdate=2015-04-14}}</ref> Ave Maria devotes four core classes to the interrelationship between law, ethics, and Catholic moral and social principles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://avemarialaw.edu/academics/Religion|title=Archived copy|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130206104017/http://www.avemarialaw.edu/academics/Religion|archivedate=2013-02-06|accessdate=2015-04-14}}</ref>\n\nThe school currently has 20 full- and 21 part-time faculty.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://abarequireddisclosures.org/|title=Standard 509 Disclosure|website=abarequireddisclosures.org|access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref>\n\n== Accreditation, bar exam passage, and employment ==\n\nIn 2016, Ave Maria School of Law was sanctioned by the American Bar Association due to lax admissions standards.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.law.com/sites/almstaff/2017/11/21/10-law-schools-sanctioned-by-aba-for-lax-admissions-outcomes/|title=10 Law Schools Sanctioned by ABA for Lax Admissions|last=Rasmussen|first=Kristen|date=November 21, 2017|work=Law.com|access-date=November 29, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanbar.org/content/dam/aba/administrative/legal_education_and_admissions_to_the_bar/governancedocuments/2016_august_ave_maria_public_notice_of_specific_remedial_action.authcheckdam.pdf|title=Ave Maria School of Law Public Notice of Specific Remedial Action|author=<!-- Not stated -->|date=August 2016|website=American Bar Association|publisher=|access-date=November 29, 2017|quote=}}</ref> In February 2018, the ABA announced the lifting of the sanctions following remedial actions by the school.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abajournal.com/news/article/aba_removes_remedial_actions_requirements_for_ave_maria_school_of_law|title=ABA removes remedial actions requirements for Ave Maria School of Law|last=Journal|first=A. B. A.|website=ABA Journal|language=en|access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, 52.6% of Ave Maria graduates who took the Florida bar exam for the first time passed, vs. a 73.9% pass rate overall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.floridabarexam.org/__85257bfe0055eb2c.nsf/52286ae9ad5d845185257c07005c3fe1/53ef72befcb1d3ec852584770066a147|title=JULY 2019 GENERAL BAR EXAMINATION|last=|first=|date=|website=Florida Board of Bar Examiners|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Ave Maria's ABA-required disclosures, 55.7% of the Class of 2018 found long-term full-time employment where a JD is required.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Campus ==\n\nAve Maria School of Law is located in northeastern Naples, Florida. The campus consists of seven major buildings located on {{convert|12|acre|m2}} in the Vineyards community: the Faculty and Administration Building;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=Vineyards|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714143259/http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=Vineyards|url-status=dead|title=Faculty and Administration Building|archivedate=Jul 14, 2014|accessdate=Apr 20, 2020}}</ref> the Law Library;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.avemarialaw.edu/library/|title=Ave Maria Law School &#124; A Florida Catholic Law School|accessdate=Apr 20, 2020}}</ref> the St. Thomas More Commons;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=Vineyards|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714143259/http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=Vineyards|url-status=dead|title=St. Thomas More Commons|archivedate=Jul 14, 2014|accessdate=Apr 20, 2020}}</ref> West and East Halls; and the Clinic/Student Organizations Building. There is an additional 16 villa-style residences available on campus for student/faculty families.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=florida|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101206114318/http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=florida|url-status=dead|title=Housing|archivedate=Dec 6, 2010|accessdate=Apr 20, 2020}}</ref> Located adjacent to the campus is the Vineyards Elementary School.\n\nThe St. Thomas More Commons contains a large classroom for 100+ students, the Moot Courtroom, the Law School Bookstore, the St. Thomas Aquinas Chapel, a student lounge and coffee shop, and the Office of Admissions.The law school inaugurated a 5,000 square feet Cancro Family Wellness Center in Jan. 2020 <ref>{{cite web|url=https://naples.floridaweekly.com/articles/ave-maria-school-of-law-receives-2-million-donation/}}</ref>\n\nThe Ave Maria Law Library is located between the Faculty and Administration Building and the St. Thomas More Commons. The collection contains Legal History, Legal Ethics, Bioethics, the Catholic Intellectual Tradition, Ancient and Medieval Philosophy, Legal Ethics and Canon Law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avemarialaw.edu/library/explore-the-library/|title=About The Collection|accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref> The Library's materials can be located and accessed via the law library online catalog.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avemarialaw.edu/library/MeetUs|title=Archived copy|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714171003/http://www.avemarialaw.edu/library/MeetUs|archivedate=2014-07-14|accessdate=2014-07-02}}</ref> In addition to serving Ave Maria Law members, the school's library is also open to the public on weekdays from 8{{nbsp}}a.m. to 5{{nbsp}}p.m.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avemarialaw.edu/library/|title=Welcome to the Ave Maria School of Law Library!|accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1999 to spring 2009, the school was located in Ann Arbor, Michigan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=aboutAve.directions|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612184447/http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=aboutAve.directions|url-status=dead|title=Location|archivedate=Jun 12, 2010|accessdate=Apr 20, 2020}}</ref> The school moved from Ann Arbor, Michigan to Naples, Florida, opening in the new location in August 2009. The move caused a great deal of controversy among the faculty and student body, with some claiming that the move jeopardized the future existence and reputation of the school.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/college_guide/feature/pie_in_the_sky.php?page=1 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-01-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091009105550/http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/college_guide/feature/pie_in_the_sky.php?page=1 |archive-date=2009-10-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\n\n''The Ave Maria Law Review'' is the only current law journal published by the Juris Doctor students at Ave Maria School of Law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=academics.LawReview|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612180537/http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=academics.LawReview|url-status=dead|title=Law Review|archivedate=Jun 12, 2010|accessdate=Apr 20, 2020}}</ref> However, the school has previously published a journal in international law,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=IntLJournal.IntLJournal|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612195940/http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=IntLJournal.IntLJournal|url-status=dead|title=International Law Journal|archivedate=Jun 12, 2010|accessdate=Apr 20, 2020}}</ref> and the school's moot court program publishes a periodical magazine called ''The Gavel''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://avemarialaw-moot-court.avemarialaw.edu/Home/Publications|title=Ave Maria Law &#124; Moot Court Board|website=avemarialaw-moot-court.avemarialaw.edu|accessdate=Apr 20, 2020}}</ref> The Law School External Affairs Office also publishes ''The Ave Maria School of Law Advocate'', a yearly publication reflecting the status of the school and current events.\n\n== Rankings ==\n\n''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' ranks Ave Maria in the fourth tier of U.S law schools.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/items/03188|title=US News and World Report Rankings|accessdate=Apr 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs reported in ''[[The Chronicle of Higher Education]]'', Ave Maria School of Law was one of 114 private colleges nationwide to fail a federal financial responsibility test in 2007, 2008, and 2009.<ref>{{cite news |title=Government says law school's financing lags |author=Karen Sloan |newspaper=The National Law Journal |date=August 13, 2010 |url=http://www.law.com/jsp/nlj/PubArticleNLJ.jsp?id=1202466359471 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=149 Nonprofit Colleges Fail Education Department's Test of Financial Strength |author=Goldie Blumenstyk and Alex Richards |newspaper=The Chronicle of Higher Education |date=August 11, 2010 |url=http://chronicle.com/article/150-Nonprofit-Colleges-Fail/123878/ |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> In a statement about the Chronicle report, the ten-year-old law school said its low asset-to-debt ratio was \"typical of recently founded institutions\" and \"represents no change in our fiscal health and should not be cause for concern\". Tom Monaghan also has committed to cover the school's operating deficits until 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.naplesnews.com/news/2009/jun/10/report-ave-maria-law-school-fails-federal-financia/ |title=Naples and Southwest Florida News and Information &#124; Naples Daily News |publisher=M.naplesnews.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref> In 2010, Ave Maria's Dean Milhizer said, \"The Law School's finances are very strong and our fundraising results were up in the fiscal year that closed June 30 compared to the past few years. We project this trend will continue and grow stronger in the years to come as our student population increases in size and fundraising results continue to improve.\" Since the move of the law school in 2009, both enrollment and selectivity of students has increased dramatically from the drop it initially suffered when the move occurred. In 2010, the school's director of external affairs, John Knowles, said the quality of the incoming classes was improving and in 2010 the school's selectivity rate improved to 46 percent\u2014the best in the school's history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aveherald.com/news/685-ave-maria-law-schools-bar-passage-rate-lags-most-florida-schools.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-10-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111015054106/http://aveherald.com/news/685-ave-maria-law-schools-bar-passage-rate-lags-most-florida-schools.html |archivedate=2011-10-15 }}</ref> Ave Maria School of Law is not affiliated with [[Ave Maria University]], which has not been cited in any federal financial test.\n\n== Costs ==\n\nThe total cost of attendance (indicating the cost of tuition, fees, and living expenses) at Ave Maria for the 2018-2019 academic year is $66,040.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Law schools in Florida]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2000]]\n[[Category:Independent law schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:Ave Maria School of Law]]\n[[Category:Education in Collier County, Florida]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Naples, Florida]]\n[[Category:Catholic law schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:2000 establishments in Florida]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Law School}}\n{{Infobox Law School\n | name           = Ave Maria School of Law\n | image          = AMSOL Logo.jpg\n | established    = 1999\n | type           = [[Private university|Private]]\n | head           = Kevin Cieply\n | city           = [[Naples, Florida|Naples]]\n | state          = [[Florida]]\n | country        = USA\n | coordinates    = {{coord|26.242147|-81.731321|type:edu|display=title,inline}}\n | [[US News and World Report|USNAWR]] Ranking = Tier Four\n | students       = 255\n | faculty        = 28\n | bar pass rate  = 52.6% (July 2019)<ref>https://www.floridabarexam.org/__85257bfe0055eb2c.nsf/52286ae9ad5d845185257c07005c3fe1/53ef72befcb1d3ec852584770066a147</ref>\n | annual tuition = $39,450\n | room and board = $13,131\n | homepage       = {{URL|http://www.avemarialaw.edu}}\n | aba profile    = [https://officialguide.lsac.org/Release/SchoolsABAData/SchoolPage/SchoolPage.aspx?sid=188]\n}}\n\n'''Ave Maria School of Law''', founded in 1999, is an [[American Bar Association|ABA]]-accredited [[Roman Catholic]] [[law school]] located in [[Naples, Florida]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanbar.org/groups/legal_education/resources/aba_approved_law_schools/in_alphabetical_order/|title=In Alphabetical Order|website=www.americanbar.org|language=en|access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref>\n\n== History and governance ==\n\n[[Tom Monaghan|Thomas S. Monaghan]], founder of [[Domino's Pizza]] and former owner of the [[Detroit Tigers]], supports the school through his Ave Maria Foundation and has served as the [[chairman of the board]] of governors of the school, which also includes [[Adam Maida|Adam Cardinal Maida]], and [[Frank Joseph Dewane]] and included, before their deaths, [[Edward Egan|Cardinal Edward Egan]], [[Bowie Kuhn]] and [[John Joseph O'Connor|John Cardinal O'Connor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://avemarialaw.edu/faculty/BoardOfGovernors|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121209070558/http://www.avemarialaw.edu/faculty/BoardOfGovernors|url-status=dead|title=Board of Governors List|archivedate=Dec 9, 2012|accessdate=Apr 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAve Maria School of Law was founded in 1999, and for the first nine years of its existence was located in [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]]. The law school's beginnings lie in discussions between future founding dean Bernard Dobranski and Monaghan. [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] Justice [[Antonin Scalia]] assisted in developing the school's curriculum, and in 1999 Supreme Court Justice [[Clarence Thomas]] delivered the school's first annual Ave Maria Lecture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=academics.Speakers|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612171923/http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=academics.Speakers|url-status=dead|title=Lectures|archivedate=Jun 12, 2010|accessdate=Apr 20, 2020}}</ref> Former professors include [[Robert Bork]].<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.avemarialaw.edu/page-section/history-timeline/|title = History Timeline\u2014Ave Maria School of Law|website = Ave Maria School of Law|language = en-US|access-date = 2016-03-11}}</ref>\n\nThe school moved from Ann Arbor, Michigan, to Naples, Florida, opening in the new location in August 2009.\n\nKevin Cieply became the third president and dean of the law school in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avemarialaw.edu/faculty/presidentanddean |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-07-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714161054/http://www.avemarialaw.edu/faculty/presidentanddean |archivedate=2014-07-14 }}</ref>\n\n== Academics and curriculum ==\n\nAve Maria School of Law offers a full-time three year [[Juris Doctor]] (J.D.) program that complements a traditional legal education based on the [[Socratic Method]] with an emphasis on how the law intersects with the Catholic intellectual tradition and [[natural law]] philosophy. The curriculum of Ave Maria School of Law includes a three-semester Legal Analysis, Writing, and Research Program as well as several required courses that focus on law and [[ethics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=academics.curriculum|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716130259/https://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=academics.curriculum|url-status=dead|title=Curriculum|archivedate=Jul 16, 2011|accessdate=Apr 20, 2020}}</ref> The school also offers various summer courses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://avemarialaw.edu/Content/academics/Schedule_Summer2014_Alpha.pdf|title=Archived copy|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414033902/http://avemarialaw.edu/Content/academics/Schedule_Summer2014_Alpha.pdf|archivedate=2015-04-14|accessdate=2015-04-14}}</ref> Ave Maria devotes four core classes to the interrelationship between law, ethics, and Catholic moral and social principles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://avemarialaw.edu/academics/Religion|title=Archived copy|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130206104017/http://www.avemarialaw.edu/academics/Religion|archivedate=2013-02-06|accessdate=2015-04-14}}</ref>\n\nThe school currently has 20 full- and 21 part-time faculty.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://abarequireddisclosures.org/|title=Standard 509 Disclosure|website=abarequireddisclosures.org|access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref>\n\n== Accreditation, bar exam passage, and employment ==\n\nIn 2016, Ave Maria School of Law was sanctioned by the American Bar Association due to lax admissions standards.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.law.com/sites/almstaff/2017/11/21/10-law-schools-sanctioned-by-aba-for-lax-admissions-outcomes/|title=10 Law Schools Sanctioned by ABA for Lax Admissions|last=Rasmussen|first=Kristen|date=November 21, 2017|work=Law.com|access-date=November 29, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanbar.org/content/dam/aba/administrative/legal_education_and_admissions_to_the_bar/governancedocuments/2016_august_ave_maria_public_notice_of_specific_remedial_action.authcheckdam.pdf|title=Ave Maria School of Law Public Notice of Specific Remedial Action|author=<!-- Not stated -->|date=August 2016|website=American Bar Association|publisher=|access-date=November 29, 2017|quote=}}</ref> In February 2018, the ABA announced the lifting of the sanctions following remedial actions by the school.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abajournal.com/news/article/aba_removes_remedial_actions_requirements_for_ave_maria_school_of_law|title=ABA removes remedial actions requirements for Ave Maria School of Law|last=Journal|first=A. B. A.|website=ABA Journal|language=en|access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, 52.6% of Ave Maria graduates who took the Florida bar exam for the first time passed, vs. a 73.9% pass rate overall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.floridabarexam.org/__85257bfe0055eb2c.nsf/52286ae9ad5d845185257c07005c3fe1/53ef72befcb1d3ec852584770066a147|title=JULY 2019 GENERAL BAR EXAMINATION|last=|first=|date=|website=Florida Board of Bar Examiners|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Ave Maria's ABA-required disclosures, 55.7% of the Class of 2018 found long-term full-time employment where a JD is required.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Campus ==\n\nAve Maria School of Law is located in northeastern Naples, Florida. The campus consists of seven major buildings located on {{convert|12|acre|m2}} in the Vineyards community: the Faculty and Administration Building;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=Vineyards|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714143259/http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=Vineyards|url-status=dead|title=Faculty and Administration Building|archivedate=Jul 14, 2014|accessdate=Apr 20, 2020}}</ref> the Law Library;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.avemarialaw.edu/library/|title=Ave Maria Law School &#124; A Florida Catholic Law School|accessdate=Apr 20, 2020}}</ref> the St. Thomas More Commons;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=Vineyards|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714143259/http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=Vineyards|url-status=dead|title=St. Thomas More Commons|archivedate=Jul 14, 2014|accessdate=Apr 20, 2020}}</ref> West and East Halls; and the Clinic/Student Organizations Building. There is an additional 16 villa-style residences available on campus for student/faculty families.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=florida|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101206114318/http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=florida|url-status=dead|title=Housing|archivedate=Dec 6, 2010|accessdate=Apr 20, 2020}}</ref> Located adjacent to the campus is the Vineyards Elementary School.\n\nThe St. Thomas More Commons contains a large classroom for 100+ students, the Moot Courtroom, the Law School Bookstore, the St. Thomas Aquinas Chapel, a student lounge and coffee shop, and the Office of Admissions.\n\nThe Ave Maria Law Library is located between the Faculty and Administration Building and the St. Thomas More Commons. The collection contains Legal History, Legal Ethics, Bioethics, the Catholic Intellectual Tradition, Ancient and Medieval Philosophy, Legal Ethics and Canon Law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avemarialaw.edu/library/explore-the-library/|title=About The Collection|accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref> The Library's materials can be located and accessed via the law library online catalog.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avemarialaw.edu/library/MeetUs|title=Archived copy|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714171003/http://www.avemarialaw.edu/library/MeetUs|archivedate=2014-07-14|accessdate=2014-07-02}}</ref> In addition to serving Ave Maria Law members, the school's library is also open to the public on weekdays from 8{{nbsp}}a.m. to 5{{nbsp}}p.m.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avemarialaw.edu/library/|title=Welcome to the Ave Maria School of Law Library!|accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1999 to spring 2009, the school was located in Ann Arbor, Michigan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=aboutAve.directions|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612184447/http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=aboutAve.directions|url-status=dead|title=Location|archivedate=Jun 12, 2010|accessdate=Apr 20, 2020}}</ref> The school moved from Ann Arbor, Michigan to Naples, Florida, opening in the new location in August 2009. The move caused a great deal of controversy among the faculty and student body, with some claiming that the move jeopardized the future existence and reputation of the school.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/college_guide/feature/pie_in_the_sky.php?page=1 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-01-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091009105550/http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/college_guide/feature/pie_in_the_sky.php?page=1 |archive-date=2009-10-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\n\n''The Ave Maria Law Review'' is the only current law journal published by the Juris Doctor students at Ave Maria School of Law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=academics.LawReview|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612180537/http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=academics.LawReview|url-status=dead|title=Law Review|archivedate=Jun 12, 2010|accessdate=Apr 20, 2020}}</ref> However, the school has previously published a journal in international law,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=IntLJournal.IntLJournal|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612195940/http://www.avemarialaw.edu/index.cfm?event=IntLJournal.IntLJournal|url-status=dead|title=International Law Journal|archivedate=Jun 12, 2010|accessdate=Apr 20, 2020}}</ref> and the school's moot court program publishes a periodical magazine called ''The Gavel''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://avemarialaw-moot-court.avemarialaw.edu/Home/Publications|title=Ave Maria Law &#124; Moot Court Board|website=avemarialaw-moot-court.avemarialaw.edu|accessdate=Apr 20, 2020}}</ref> The Law School External Affairs Office also publishes ''The Ave Maria School of Law Advocate'', a yearly publication reflecting the status of the school and current events.\n\n== Rankings ==\n\n''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' ranks Ave Maria in the fourth tier of U.S law schools.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/items/03188|title=US News and World Report Rankings|accessdate=Apr 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs reported in ''[[The Chronicle of Higher Education]]'', Ave Maria School of Law was one of 114 private colleges nationwide to fail a federal financial responsibility test in 2007, 2008, and 2009.<ref>{{cite news |title=Government says law school's financing lags |author=Karen Sloan |newspaper=The National Law Journal |date=August 13, 2010 |url=http://www.law.com/jsp/nlj/PubArticleNLJ.jsp?id=1202466359471 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=149 Nonprofit Colleges Fail Education Department's Test of Financial Strength |author=Goldie Blumenstyk and Alex Richards |newspaper=The Chronicle of Higher Education |date=August 11, 2010 |url=http://chronicle.com/article/150-Nonprofit-Colleges-Fail/123878/ |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> In a statement about the Chronicle report, the ten-year-old law school said its low asset-to-debt ratio was \"typical of recently founded institutions\" and \"represents no change in our fiscal health and should not be cause for concern\". Tom Monaghan also has committed to cover the school's operating deficits until 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.naplesnews.com/news/2009/jun/10/report-ave-maria-law-school-fails-federal-financia/ |title=Naples and Southwest Florida News and Information &#124; Naples Daily News |publisher=M.naplesnews.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref> In 2010, Ave Maria's Dean Milhizer said, \"The Law School's finances are very strong and our fundraising results were up in the fiscal year that closed June 30 compared to the past few years. We project this trend will continue and grow stronger in the years to come as our student population increases in size and fundraising results continue to improve.\" Since the move of the law school in 2009, both enrollment and selectivity of students has increased dramatically from the drop it initially suffered when the move occurred. In 2010, the school's director of external affairs, John Knowles, said the quality of the incoming classes was improving and in 2010 the school's selectivity rate improved to 46 percent\u2014the best in the school's history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aveherald.com/news/685-ave-maria-law-schools-bar-passage-rate-lags-most-florida-schools.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-10-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111015054106/http://aveherald.com/news/685-ave-maria-law-schools-bar-passage-rate-lags-most-florida-schools.html |archivedate=2011-10-15 }}</ref> Ave Maria School of Law is not affiliated with [[Ave Maria University]], which has not been cited in any federal financial test.\n\n== Costs ==\n\nThe total cost of attendance (indicating the cost of tuition, fees, and living expenses) at Ave Maria for the 2018-2019 academic year is $66,040.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Law schools in Florida]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2000]]\n[[Category:Independent law schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:Ave Maria School of Law]]\n[[Category:Education in Collier County, Florida]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Naples, Florida]]\n[[Category:Catholic law schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:2000 establishments in Florida]]\n", "name_user": "Centrodejusticia", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCampus:added new information on additional building facility", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ave_Maria_School_of_Law"}
{"title_page": "Croque, Newfoundland and Labrador", "text_new": "{{Location map|Canada Newfoundland and Labrador|lat=51.0580|long=-55.8378|width=200|caption=Location of Croque in [[Newfoundland and Labrador]]|label=Croque}} '''Croque''' is a [[List of communities in Newfoundland and Labrador|settlement]] in [[Newfoundland and Labrador]] with a population of 51 (2016).<ref>Canadian Census of 2016, [https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=DPL&Code1=100199&Geo2=PR&Code2=10&Data=Count&SearchText=Croque&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1 'Croque'].</ref>\n\nCroque is the name given by the English to Havre Du Croc. Translated, Croque means Crunch. Havre Du Croc means Harbour Of The Hook. It was also known as Baie Du Croc.\n\nCroc is pronounced Crow in French. The second c is silent.\n\nThe harbour is shaped like a boat hook or gaff. The spelling \"Croque\" appeared on James Cook's charts. Croc was used by French fishermen as far back as 1504. Part of it was called Le Petit Maistre. It was where after 1640 all French ships and crews registered in the spring for their assigned fishing \"berths.\" The first captain to arrive became the Admiral of the region for the season. \n\nSir David Kirke reported a massacre that occurred in Croc in the early 1600s. Twenty-one French fishermen were slain presumably by native \"Indians.\" However, history has not proven that \"Indians\" were involved.\n\nFor over two hundred years Croc was the headquarters for the French navy in Western & Northern Newfoundland & Labrador. It was a coal storage, supply station and repair station for the sailing and hybrid ships. It contained an iron works forge, sail makers shop, carpenter shop, bakery, bunk houses and a farm. In the latter part of the 19th century the French hired Irish guardians to care for their property in winter.\n\n1763 to 1766 were busy years in Croc. Sir James Cook was there charting the coast, Sir Joseph Banks was there collecting plant samples, West Country merchant John Phipps had built a mansion there called \"Crusoe Hall\", and the Moravian missionaries dropped by for a visit before they moved on to Labrador.\n\nAfter the Entente Cordiale in 1904 the French completely abandoned the area and  Havre Du Croc developed into the Irish communities of Southwest Croque and Kearney's Cove.\n\nBetween 1956 and 1959 both communities relocated to the bottom of the bay to the area called L'Epine Cadoret - the site of a French/English cemetery dating back to the early 1700s. The present day community is called Croque.\n\nIt once was a thriving fishing and logging community. However, since the indefinite cod moratorium of 1992 it is struggling to survive. It is still a popular tourist destination because of the historic cemetery, waterfront fishing properties, names of ships carved into the rocks at various locations, its deep secluded harbour (referred to by captains as \"God's Pocket\"), moose hunting, salmon and trout sports fishing, and beautiful seascapes. Population now is less than 50.\n\nCroque,NL,CA (Havre Du Croc, Terre Neuve) by Francis R. Reardon Sr.\n\n==References==\n{{Footnotes}}\n{{coord|51.058|N|55.837|W|display=title|region:CA_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Newfoundland and Labrador]]\n\n\n{{Newfoundland-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Location map|Canada Newfoundland and Labrador|lat=51.0580|long=-55.8378|width=200|caption=Location of Croque in [[Newfoundland and Labrador]]|label=Croque}} '''Croque''' is a [[List of communities in Newfoundland and Labrador|settlement]] in [[Newfoundland and Labrador]] with a population of 51 (2016).<ref>Canadian Census of 2016, [https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=DPL&Code1=100199&Geo2=PR&Code2=10&Data=Count&SearchText=Croque&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1 'Croque'].</ref>\n\nCroque is the name given by the English to Havre Du Croc. Translated, Croque means Crunch.  Havre Du Croc means  Harbour Of The Hook. It was also known as Baie Du Croc.\n\nCroc is pronounced Crow in French. The second c is silent.\n\nThe harbour is shaped like a boat hook or gaff. The spelling \"Croque\" appeared on James Cook's charts.Croc was used by French fishermen as far back as 1504. Part of it was called Le Petit Maistre. It was where after 1640 all French ships and crews registered in the spring for their assigned fishing \"berths.\"  The first captain to arrive became the Admiral of the region for the season. \n\nSir David Kirke reported a massacre that occurred in Croc in the early 1600s. Twenty-one French fishermen were slain presumably by native \"Indians.\" However, history has not proven that \"Indians\" were involved.\n\nFor over two hundred years Croc was the headquarters for the French navy in Western & Northern Newfoundland & Labrador. It was a coal storage,  supply station and repair station  for the sailing and hybrid ships. It contained an iron works forge, sail makers shop, carpenter shop, bakery, bunk houses and a farm. In the latter part of the 19th century the French hired Irish guardians to care for their property in winter.\n\n1763 to 1766 were busy years in Croc. Sir James Cook was there charting the coast, Sir Joseph Banks was there collecting plant samples, West Country merchant John Phipps had built a mansion there called \"Crusoe Hall\", and the Moravian  missionaries dropped by for a visit before they moved on to Labrador.\n\nAfter the Entente Cordiale in 1904 the French completely abandoned the area and  Havre Du Croc developed into the Irish communities of Southwest Croque and Kearney's Cove.\n\nBetween 1956 and 1959 both communities relocated to the bottom of the bay to the area called L'Epine Cadoret - the site of a French/English cemetery dating back to the early 1700s. The present day community is called Croque.\n\nIt once was a thriving fishing and logging community. However, since the indefinite cod moratorium of 1992 it is struggling to survive. It is still a popular tourist destination because of the historic cemetery, waterfront fishing properties, names of ships carved into the rocks at various locations, its deep secluded harbour (referred to by captains as \"God's Pocket\"), moose hunting, salmon and trout sports fishing, and beautiful seascapes. Population now is less than 50.\n\nCroque,NL,CA (Havre Du Croc, Terre Neuve)  by Francis R. Reardon Sr.\n\n==References==\n{{Footnotes}}\n{{coord|51.058|N|55.837|W|display=title|region:CA_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Newfoundland and Labrador]]\n\n\n{{Newfoundland-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ycleymans", "label": "safe", "comment": "deleted dubble spaces", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Croque,_Newfoundland_and_Labrador"}
{"title_page": "Fastron-Metro TV Europe Asia Expedition", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=August 2016}}\n{{one source|date=February 2012}}\n}}\n\n'''Fastron-Metro TV Europe Asia Expedition''' is an Indonesian expedition team who travel around the world by surface using 4x4 vehicles. The trip across the 15 countries started from Indonesia to Venice Italy. The five-month journey traces the Silk Road trade route that crosses the continent of Asia to Europe.\n\n==Team members==\n* Bucek (Leader)\n* [http://bastamanography.id/ Dr. Bastaman] (Expedition and Wilderness Medical Expert Consultant - [http://medicadventurer.net Medicadventurer\u2122])\n* Hendri Ismaoen (Producer/reporter Metro TV)\n* Yeremia Leo (Cameraman Metro TV)\n* Meckry Raditya (Expedition driver)\n* Ibnu Hajar (Expedition driver)\n* Anastasia Rijkers (Producer/PR Metro TV)\n* Irvan Liberty (Reporter Media Indonesia)\n* Basuki Widiasto (Editor/IT support and communication Metro TV)\n* [http://medicadventurer.com/ Dr. Andrianto (Expedition Doctor - Medicadventurer\u2122 Indonesia)]\n* Ibnu Purwanto (Technical crew)\n* Crack Palinggi (Photographer)\n* Agus Siswanto (Expedition driver)\n* Yana Mulyana (Logistic manager)\n\n==Countries crossed by the team==\nFrom Indonesia they crossed 15 countries:\n* [[Malaysia]]\n* [[Thailand]]\n* [[Laos]]\n* [[China]]\n* [[Kirgiztan]]\n* [[Kazakhstan]]\n* [[Uzbekistan]]\n* [[Turkmenistan]]\n* [[Iran]]\n* [[Turkey]]\n* [[Bulgaria]]\n* [[Serbia]]\n* [[Hungary]]\n* [[Austria]]\n* [[Italy]]\n\n==Episode 1==\nIn the first episode the team start the trip from Indonesia to Malaysia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metrotvnews.com/read/newsprograms/2011/12/31/11085/88/Fastron-Metro-TV-Europe-Asia-Expedition-Episode-1 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120909041453/http://www.metrotvnews.com/read/newsprograms/2011/12/31/11085/88/Fastron-Metro-TV-Europe-Asia-Expedition-Episode-1 |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 9, 2012 |title=Episode 1 |date=November 26, 2011 }}</ref> Preparing the vehicle is shown, then sending the vehicle by sea, until the team remove the vehicle from the port of Port Klang Malaysia.\n\n==Episode 2==\nThe team go to Melaka,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://metrotvnews.com/read/newsprograms/2011/12/31/11085/88/Fastron-Metro-TV-Europe-Asia-Expedition-Episode-II |title=Episode 2 |date=December 3, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120710064401/http://metrotvnews.com/read/newsprograms/2011/12/31/11085/88/Fastron-Metro-TV-Europe-Asia-Expedition-Episode-II |archivedate=July 10, 2012 }}</ref> which is a place located in the coastal area of Malaysia where there are buildings or Portuguese, Dutch, and English heritage.\n\nAfter Melaka, the four-car team continue the journey to Penang. Before reaching Penang, Tim takes time to stop at Bukit Jugra, a place known for paragliding sport. The team try flying from the hills here.\n\n==Episode 3==\nThey enter Thailand<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metrotvnews.com/read/newsprograms/2011/12/31/11085/88/Fastron-Metro-TV-Europe-Asia-Expedition-Episode-III |title=Episode 3 |date=December 10, 2011 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> which is hit by massive flooding and see how the Thai people fight against the disaster.\n\n==Episode 4==\nAfter Malaysia and Thailand, the team in episode travel to the former French colony of Laos.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://metrotvnews.com/read/newsprograms/2011/12/31/11085/88/Fastron-Metro-TV-Europe-Asia-Expedition-Episode-IV |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120716232638/http://metrotvnews.com/read/newsprograms/2011/12/31/11085/88/Fastron-Metro-TV-Europe-Asia-Expedition-Episode-IV |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 16, 2012 |title=Episode 4 |date=December 17, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nBuddhism is the religion of the majority of Laos.\n\nThe team go to Batuxay Park and see buildings that resemble temples, one is Wat Si Saket Museum. Wat Si Saket Temple was built in 1819-1824 during the reign of King Anouvong, the last ruler Tiane Vien.\n\nThe team then continued on to Luang Prabang.\n\n==Episode 5==\nAfter three days journey from the border, the team arrived at the People's Republic of China.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metrotvnews.com/read/newsprograms/2011/12/31/11085/88/Fastron-Metro-TV-Europe-Asia-Expedition-Episode-V |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120909170812/http://www.metrotvnews.com/read/newsprograms/2011/12/31/11085/88/Fastron-Metro-TV-Europe-Asia-Expedition-Episode-V |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 9, 2012 |title=Episode 5 |date=December 24, 2011 }}</ref> The team stopped at the city of Chengdu, an industrial city in China. Although Chengdu is an industrial city, many historic buildings are well maintained.\n\n==Episode 6==\nThe expedition continues into China<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metrotvnews.com/read/newsprograms/2011/12/31/11085/88/Fastron-Metro-TV-Europe-Asia-Expedition-Episode-VI |title=Episode 6 |date=December 31, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120108023322/http://www.metrotvnews.com/read/newsprograms/2011/12/31/11085/88/Fastron-Metro-TV-Europe-Asia-Expedition-Episode-VI |archivedate=2012-01-08 }}</ref> and spends 19 days there. After passing through the borders of Kirgizstan, the expedition continues toy to Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, Iran, and Turkey.\n\nAfter traveling over 27,000 kilometers, the team arrives in Italy, the goal of the expedition.\n\n==Vehicle==\nThe team used four 4x4 [[Toyota Fortuner]] vehicles.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [[Pertamina]]\n* [http://medicadventurer.com/ Medicadventurer\u2122 Indonesia]\n\n[[Category:Explorers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=August 2016}}\n{{one source|date=February 2012}}\n}}\n\n'''Fastron-Metro TV Europe Asia Expedition''' is an Indonesian expedition team who travel around the world by surface using 4x4 vehicles. The trip across the 15 countries started from Indonesia to Venice Italy. The five-month journey traces the Silk Road trade route that crosses the continent of Asia to Europe.\n\n==Team members==\n* Bucek (Leader)\n* [http://bastamanography.id/ Dr. Bastaman] (Expedition and Wilderness Medical Expert Consultant - [http://medicadventurer.net Medicadventurer\u2122])\n* Hendri Ismaoen (Producer/reporter Metro TV)\n* Yeremia Leo (Cameraman Metro TV)\n* Meckry Raditya (Expedition driver)\n* Ibnu Hajar (Expedition driver)\n* Anastasia Rijkers (Producer/PR Metro TV)\n* Irvan Liberty (Reporter Media Indonesia)\n* Basuki Widiasto (Editor/IT support and communication Metro TV)\n* [http://medicadventurer.com/ Dr. Andrianto (Expedition Doctor - Medicadventurer\u2122 Indonesia)]\n* Ibnu Purwanto (Technical crew)\n* Crack Palinggi (Photographer)\n* Agus Siswanto (Expedition driver)\n* Yana Mulyana (Logistic manager)\n\n==Countries crossed by the team==\nFrom Indonesia they crossed 15 countries:\n* [[Malaysia]]\n* [[Thailand]]\n* [[Laos]]\n* [[China]]\n* [[Kirgiztan]]\n* [[Kazakhstan]]\n* [[Uzbekistan]]\n* [[Turkmenistan]]\n* [[Iran]]\n* [[Turkey]]\n* [[Bulgaria]]\n* [[Serbia]]\n* [[Hungary]]\n* [[Austria]]\n* [[Italy]]\n\n==Episode 1==\nIn the first episode the team start the trip from Indonesia to Malaysia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metrotvnews.com/read/newsprograms/2011/12/31/11085/88/Fastron-Metro-TV-Europe-Asia-Expedition-Episode-1 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120909041453/http://www.metrotvnews.com/read/newsprograms/2011/12/31/11085/88/Fastron-Metro-TV-Europe-Asia-Expedition-Episode-1 |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 9, 2012 |title=Episode 1 |date=November 26, 2011 }}</ref> Preparing the vehicle is shown, then sending the vehicle by sea, until the team remove the vehicle from the port of Port Klang Malaysia.\n\n==Episode 2==\nThe team go to Melaka,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://metrotvnews.com/read/newsprograms/2011/12/31/11085/88/Fastron-Metro-TV-Europe-Asia-Expedition-Episode-II |title=Episode 2 |date=December 3, 2011 |url-statu